He was released one day later.
The man works as a volunteer for the diocese of Nantes and was responsible for closing the cathedral on the eve of the fire.
Since there was no trace of a violent penetration into the church, he quickly became the focus of the investigators.
Discuss the abolition of the 50 + 1 rule
Former DFB President Reinhard Grindel has recommended thinking about abolishing the 50 + 1 rule.
"German football should at least discuss setting conditions and clear rules for investors before the EU Commission creates completed facts," Grindel said to the "Bild am Sonntag".
He stressed: "The 50 + 1 rules do not work for the clubs that are most likely to become dangerous in Bavaria and Dortmund: see Leipzig or Leverkusen.
In this respect, one cannot avoid the debate as to whether it is not necessary to facilitate the involvement of investors in associations that want to break into this phalanx ".
However, he has doubts as to whether there is a willingness in the German Football League to allow majority participation, which is prohibited in the Bundesliga by the 50 + 1 rule.
"It remains a legal risk to draw investment fences around the business location of the Bundesliga in a single European market," said Grindel.
The former head of the DFB sees the danger that "the attempts to ensure more competitive balance in the Bundesliga ultimately only weaken the competitiveness of our top clubs at the European level, but do not lead to more excitement in the championship".
Even an equal distribution of the TV funds will not achieve a decisive effect.
"FC Bayern has a turnover of 750 million euros, Borussia Dortmund 500 million and RB Leipzig 300 million.
The differences are therefore immense among the first three clubs alone.
The other 15 clubs have an average budget of 130 million, "said the 58-year-old.
Looking at the past, Grindel feels betrayed.
"Unfortunately, there have been people who noticed this mistake and pierced the press instead of addressing me," said Grindel about the adoption of an expensive watch that led to his resignation in April 2019.
"This has already been a human concern for me."
He received the gift of about 11,000 euros from a Ukrainian official.
"I have committed a compliance violation and it was right to draw the consequences from it," said Grindel.
"I used the ominous watch gift in a completely transparent and unsuspecting way.
Many in the DFB knew about it. "
He never "made a secret of the gift," assured the 58-year-old.
"That may be called naive, at least this form of transparency was the complete opposite of corruption."
"Black Lives Matter": injured and a dead man
The protests against police violence in the United States have been sharpened by Donald Trump's use of federal police in several cities.
On Saturday there were clashes between protesters and policemen in various cities.
Three people were injured in Louisville, and 16 people were arrested in Seattle.
In Austin, a person was killed by gunfire while a demonstration march was crossing a crossing.
Previously, protests against racism and police violence had once again led to clashes in Portland.
The security forces, including officials from the Federal Police, used tear gas on the night of Saturday and forcibly dispersed protesters.
Hundreds of protesters, some armed, marched through Louisville on Saturday in Kentucky, demanding that those responsible for the death of Breonna Taylor be held responsible.
The 26-year-old student was shot dead in a drug raid in her home in Louisville in March.
The target of the raid was someone else who did not live there at all, and no drugs were found.
On Saturday, when a member of a group calling itself an armed alliance of black Americans fired a shot, three people were injured.
According to the NBC, they were taken to the hospital.
None of them was in danger of life.
The police set up barricades because counter-demonstrators of a white militia had also formed.
In the end, there was no meeting between the two groups.
In Austin, Texas, a person was shot and killed in the course of a "Black Lives Matter" demonstration.
The police detained a suspect.
She has not yet provided any further information on the circumstances of the offence.
Mayor Steve Adler told the New York Times that he, like many in the city, was "inconsolable and stunned" about what had happened.
Also in the American metropolis of Seattle, protesters clashed with the police on Saturday.
They set fire to construction cars in front of a youth prison, and the police used iridescent grenades and pepper spray.
According to the Seattle Times, 16 people were arrested for resistance to police or bodily harm.
A court building was set on fire in the city of Oakland, California.
A small group of protesters hit windows, fired fireworks, and laser-dazzled police officers, the Oakland police reported late on Saturday evening (local time).
The fire was quickly extinguished.
In Aurora, a suburb of Denver, Colorado, a car drove through a crowd demonstrating on a highway.
According to the police, one of the protesters fired a weapon and at least one person was injured in the hospital.
There were also windows in a court and a fire was set, as reported by the police.
Investigations were started.
Rakoczy in Bad Kissingen: Historical costumes defy Corona
Although the big snack was missing in the spa town, visitors and performers enjoyed the Rakoczy flair of the alternative program.
It was unusual for visitors, performers and organizers: the Rakoczy weekend without a Rakoczy festival.
But: Even if the big party mile was missing in the city center, the crowds and program highlights like Saale is burning, Rakoczy-Ball or the parade, many got their money's worth with the Corona-compliant alternative program.
"I think we have succeeded in spreading Rakoczy flair," says spa director Sylvie Thormann.
The guests would have accepted it well.
In principle, one returns to the beginnings of the Rakoczy festival, as the historical ones were also the focus of the festival.
Pleasant atmosphere
Vesna Konhäuser has always visited with her husband for more than 25 years at the Rakoczy-Fest Bad Kissingen.
Also this time in the Corona year.
The couple have made themselves comfortable at the Luitpold Casino, watching the history while strolling and listening to the Cuban live music at the casino restaurant.
"I also find it so pleasant," says Konhäuser.
It does not miss the crowds that are otherwise part of Rakoczy.
But you miss the usual programme highlights, especially Saale on Friday night and the historic parade and fireworks display on Sunday night.
"That's a pity.
The weather would have been great this year, "she says.
Rakoczy equestrian tournament to take place again
For the performers of the historic spa guests, the alternative program meant more work.
For example, Christina Gold, who participates in the parade in a normal year and can be seen there on the carriage of the Kurgarten cafe.
This year she was walking in costume on Saturdays and Sundays in the city.
"That's more strenuous, otherwise we'll have it easier," she says.
The equestrian club had less to do, even though individual riders were traveling in the park.
"We very much hope that the equestrian quadrille will be able to take place again next year," says Ulrike Waldhofen.
She announced that after a break of several years in 2021, another Rakoczy equestrian tournament will take place.
28 Corona cases with Spanish second-division club Fuenlabrada
The Spanish second division football club CF Fuenlabrada is sliding deeper into the crisis due to a Corona outbreak.
Since the newcomer from near Madrid had flown to a match in the city of A Coruña on July 20, despite the first Corona cases, a low impact follows the next.
Until Sunday 28 players or team members had been tested positive, one of them came to the hospital, as the club reported.
Fuenlabrada from the city of the same name southwest of Madrid had the chance to reach the promotion playoffs.
Now even the descent into the B-Group of the Second League is threatening.
The match against Deportivo La Coruña last Monday was cancelled at the last moment, the prosecutor's office investigated for a possible offence against public health, the top sports authority CSD is considering the forced descent of the club.
Players and other team members are quarantined in a hotel.
"Until the sixth day of quarantine, they did not get a fresh towel and gel," wrote the sports newspaper "AS".
On photos, players can be seen hanging underwear and club clothes in their rooms in the hotel for drying after they apparently had to wash them themselves.
Also, the bedding was not changed for five days.
Another problem is the food.
Neither good nor sufficient, "AS" wrote.
However, the club announced that they were satisfied with the hotel.
The club's attorney, Javier Tebas Llanas, rejected the accusation of deliberately endangering public health.
The son of the president of the Spanish Primera Division, Javier Tebas, as reported by the news agency Europa Press and the sports newspaper "Marca", did not violate the Corona rules set up by the Football Association.
Before the flight, there were four infected people until 19 July, but they were all isolated and had not travelled with them.
Just before the flight on Monday to A Coruña, all players and team members were tested again.
When the team was already in A Coruña, the corona test was positive for "five or six" other team members.
The game was cancelled 60 minutes before the kick-off, Tebas Llanas said.
