Radprofi Tony Martin: Career continuation imaginable
Time trial specialist Tony Martin is thinking about continuing his career.
Frankfurt / Main - The seven-time time trial world champion Tony Martin can well imagine to continue his cycling career.
"I am currently setting the conditions with the team, how and in which form it could continue," said the 35-year-old of the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung".
Martin is currently employed by the Dutch team Jumbo-Visma and had considered ending his career this year before the Corona break.
The negotiations with his team are also about the number of race days, he said.
Or about other problems that would plague him as a family father, said Martin.
He used to stand up after a fall, and the first thought was: "Quickly return to the wheel.
Today, as the father of a little daughter, I think: what if ".
The professional cyclist admitted that there are aspects with which he is increasingly difficult.
"But it was good for me to remember from the Corona time what I got from cycling and how much fun it is for me".
The time trial specialist returns to competition at the Tour de l'Ain (5 to 9 August).
Bavaria: At least four dead on Bavaria's streets at the weekend
The beautiful weather attracts bikers on the streets in many places.
For at least three people, the motorcycle tour ends deadly.
An 18-year-old pedestrian also dies.
Schönthal - In accidents on Bavaria's streets, several, mostly young people died on the weekend.
An 18-year-old motorcyclist was caught on Saturday near Schönthal (Cham district) by a car, which came on the opposite track.
At first, it was unclear why the car was on the opposite track.
On Saturday, in Upper Bavaria, a 22-year-old collided with a horse carriage on his machine.
He was walking downhill at Beilngries, according to the police.
In a left turn, he bounced against the carriage.
His injuries were so severe that he died at the scene of the accident.
Of the twelve passengers on the carriage, one man was severely injured and one man was slightly injured, as reported by the police.
In another fatal accident, an 18-year-old died in Bad Kötzting, Upper Palatinate.
He had laid down on a road on Sunday night and was overrun by a 42-year-old driver.
According to the police, the 18-year-old wanted to sleep.
The driver could no longer brake in time.
At Schönberg (district of Freyung-Grafenau) on Saturday, a 57 year old biker collided frontally against a car in a right-hand bend despite full braking.
He died in the accident.
The 57-year-old driver suffered a shock, the other three people in the car remained uninjured.
The safety of motorcyclists was discussed on Saturday by Bavaria's Minister of Transport Kerstin Schreyer (CSU).
In a letter to the organiser of the biker protests announced for August against driving bans, Gabor Kovacs, the Minister referred to extensive investments such as underride protection at guardrails and the defusing of dangerous curves.
"For the safety of motorcyclists, we have achieved a lot in recent years," the letter said.
"The number of motorized two-wheelers killed decreased by around 28 percent compared to 2011."
