Argentina rejects counter-offer of creditors
The new demands could not be met, the Ministry of Economy in Buenos Aires announced on Saturday.
"This would not only be irresponsible, but also unjust," said a statement.
"While 50 percent of children in Argentina live in poverty, we cannot increase the short-term profits of our creditors."
The debts of the second largest economy in South America are no longer viable under current conditions.
This is why Argentina is asking its private creditors to waive some of their claims of around USD 66 billion (around EUR 59 billion).
If no agreement is reached, the country will again face state bankruptcy.
It would be the ninth payment default in Argentine history.
Most recently, lenders had demanded higher interest rates on government bonds and changes to some contractual clauses.
However, the Argentine government maintains its last offer and is not prepared to make any further concessions.
Argentina is in a serious financial and economic crisis.
Most recently, the inflation rate was more than 50 percent.
Experts expect economic power to decline by around ten percent in the current year.
At the end of May, Argentina had not settled interest receivables amounting to 503 million US dollars and had thus slipped into a limited default.
Professionally arrived - private not yet
Dr. Stefanie Kramer draws this conclusion after her first days at the notary's office in Eggenfelden.
In the end, everything went very fast: In the middle of May, Dr. Stefanie Kramer learned that she will succeed Lutz Feller in the Eggenfelden notarial office.
Already six weeks later, at the beginning of July, the doctoral lawyer took up the work, the normal day-to-day business is already in full swing.
"However, I still have to arrive privately," she explains in conversation with the Rottaler Anzeiger and laughs.
The short lead time did not suffice, of course, to shift the center of life from Regensburg completely to Eggenfelden, reports the native Dingolfinger.
She is currently looking for a suitable apartment or house in the city with her husband, who works as a judge at the district court in Regensburg.
At least her husband was still able to apply for parental leave at short notice in order to ensure the care of the two daughters (3 ½ and 1 ½ years old).
In order not to have to commute every day from Regensburg, she also has an overnight stay with her parents in Dingolfing, explains the 39-year-old.
Grown up in the neighboring district, the town of Eggenfelden has of course long been known to it.
During visits with her family in recent months, she has then again stated: "Eggenfelden is a really beautiful small town".
She was all the more pleased that she had made the race in the selection process for the vacancy.
Also in Dr. Stefanie Kramer's professional career, her home of Lower Bavaria plays a central role: After studying law in Passau, she completed her internship and the 2nd state examination in Regensburg.
After several positions as a notary assessor, among others in Rehau and Hof in Upper Franconia, Babenhausen in the Unterallgäu and Regensburg - during this time she also shouldered her doctorate in labour law - she took her first position as a notary in Rotthalmünster in the district of Passau in 2012.
In 2016, she was on parental leave and then moved to Regensburg.
Since then, he has served in various notarial offices.
When the job in Eggenfelden was advertised because of the approaching retirement of Lutz Feller, she saw the right time for the full professional return, explains the 39-year-old.
The team of its predecessor, who in the future takes over the holiday representation in the notarial office, Dr. Stefanie Kramer completely took over - and has immediately a praise for the team of the law firm ready: "It is going very well!"
The fact that she can rely on well-established processes makes it easier for her to take care of the pending relocation of the private centre of gravity.
In terms of nursery and nursery places, she has already contacted a local institution.
And if everything works out as desired, she hopes to pursue her hobby here too soon - and to get to know the most beautiful jogging routes of the Rottal.
BVB plans for league start with a maximum of 15,000 spectators
Dortmund The largest German football stadium in Dortmund will not be filled to 20 percent at the start of the season in case of a fan return.
"Due to the distance regulation, which must be compelled to be complied with, we plan to have 12,000 to 15,000 spectators at present," Borussia Dortmund's managing director Carsten Cramer said to the "Tagesspiegel".
Usually the arena in the district city holds a little more than 81,000 spectators at Bundesliga matches.
The BVB lost about four million euros per game in the ghost games caused by the Corona pandemic last season.
The Cramer, who is responsible for marketing, digitalization and internationalization at the BVB, hopes that, in addition to the normal spectator seats, some of the approximately 4000 seats in the hospitality sector can be opened again: "It is of course a blow to the office if these revenues completely break away".
In view of the ongoing Corona crisis, everyone is currently "well advised to take a stable sideline first".
"If many companies are not doing well and 6.8 million people are in short-time work in Germany alone, then the need is limited to entertainment," said Cramer.
The Dortmund marketing boss praised the BVB pros for their salary partial waiver, which is intended to help overcome the crisis: "Of course, players know that their salary waiver has a different effect than when we put 100 people working in merchandising on short-time work."
Tiny wonders: early start to life with a few hundred grams
Barely heavier than a packer of butter, just three tablespoons of blood in his entire body: that was Gabriel when he was born - he weighed exactly 273 grams.
The Bub is one of about 400 premature babies that are taken care of at the Grazer Kinderklinik every year.
A quarter of them weighs less than 1,500 grams, a few - like Gabriel and his brothers Raphael and Michael - are extreme lightweight with less than a kilogram of birth weight.
They are so small and so early that neither lungs, nor intestines, nor muscles are fully developed.
Sometimes your skin is so delicate that it could hurt the electrodes of an ECG.
And they are so tiny that they sometimes wear doll clothes and mini diapers specially made for them.
But not so small that they are not in the voice - "and how", Berndt Urlesberger smiles.
"Even if, of course, they don't shout as loud as big babies."
When the whiteboard becomes the stage
Despite Corona Theater in the classroom: The Whiteboard as a stage experienced the 9th classes of the St. Jakobus-Gymnasium in Abtsgmünd shortly before the start of the holiday.
Actress Julia Sylvester from the Theater der Stadt Aalen presented the production "Das Heimatkleid" to the pupils - by video.
The students were then able to talk to the actress and director Winfried Tobias via Skype about the play and the performance.
The idea for the performance format from the current Corona situation had been born.
Teacher Teresa Nar was happy about the enrichment of the lessons.
Even if at the end all participants agreed that the direct encounter in the theater and stage space would offer additional stimuli, one sees in the theater also the potentials for the contact in the schools.
"If we continue to improve the technical framework, this could be an interesting addition to the game," emphasized director Winfried Tobias.
