"Gone with the Wind": Film legend Olivia de Havilland is dead
The film legend and Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland is dead.
She died on Sunday in Paris at the age of 104 of a natural death, confirmed her spokeswoman for the German press agency.
De Havilland was known for her role as Melanie Hamilton in the southern epic "Vom Winde beweht" (1939).
Born to British parents in Tokyo, Olivia de Havilland moved to California as an infant.
The Austrian theatre man Max Reinhardt discovered the 19-year-old in the role of Hermia of Shakespeare's "Midsummer Night's Dream".
The film studio Warner Brothers signed her for seven years and released her at the side of Eroll Flynn.
She made eight films with the heartbreaker.
In 1946 she won her first Oscar in the leading role of "To Each His Own".
The film was screened in Germany under the title "Mother's Heart".
Three years later, the award came as the best actress in William Wylers "The Heiress".
She also received much recognition as a neurotic eccentric in "Der dunkle Spiegel" and "Die Schlangengrube".
Daphne du Maurier suggested her in 1952 for the lead role in the film adaptation of her novel "My Cousin Rachel".
The play became a worldwide success.
With her longtime girlfriend Bette Davis she played in "Wiegenlied für eine Leiche".
The son Benjamin was born from his marriage to the writer Marcus Goodrich (1946 to 1953).
In Paris, de Havilland married the journalist Pierre Paul Galante and had his daughter Gisèle with him.
This marriage also broke up.
However, rumors of an affair with former British Prime Minister Edward Heath were never confirmed.
"Road to Timmendorf": Beach volleyball: Thole / Wickler miss Final at Comeback
Julius Thole and Clemens Wickler missed the final at the beach volleyball tournament "Road to Timmendorf".
At the meeting of the top teams in Düsseldorf, they lost 1: 2 (17: 21, 21: 17, 19: 21) to their national team colleagues Nils Ehlers and Lars Flüggen in the semifinals.
Last Thole / Wickler had played in September of last year at the World Tour Final in Rome.
In the final on the Rhine, their conquerors Ehlers / Flüggen beat the surprise team Lukas Pfretschner and his interim partner Steven van de Velde by a defeat of 0: 2 (17: 21, 17: 21).
In addition to the show tournament, three starting places for the German championships were played at the beginning of September in Timmendorfer Strand: The tickets were secured by Armin Dollinger / Simon Kulzer, Manuel Harms / Richard Peemüller and Simon Pfretschner / Milan Sievers.
Veal ejection from AfD confirmed - FDP speaks of "fig leaf"
From the point of view of the FDP, the exclusion of Andreas Kalbitz from the AfD is only a "fig leaf" and does not change the character of the party.
"The AfD is the parliamentary arm of the right-wing extremists in Germany.
Andreas Kalbitz is only part of the tip of the iceberg of the radicals in the AfD, "said the FDP interior politician Benjamin Strasser of the news agency dpa in Berlin.
The Federal Court of Arbitration of the AfD had confirmed on Saturday in Stuttgart after several hours of trial the exclusion of Kalbitz, which the Federal Executive Board had decided by majority in May.
Kalbitz is chairman of the AfD faction in the Brandenburger Landtag.
"If the AfD really wanted to consistently remove right-wing extremists from their party, functionaries like Björn Höcke and his supporters would have long since been excluded," Strasser said.
"However, there is no political will in the AfD because right-wing extremism is now part of the party."
CSU General Secretary Markus Blume said similarly: "That Andreas Kalbitz is now excluded says nothing and does not change anything," he said to the "Welt am Sonntag".
"Rather, it speaks volumes, how many frenetic supporters a right-wing extremist in the middle of the AfD still has".
Blume assumes that the AfD will again fall below five percent in future elections.
"The days of the AfD in the parliaments are counted".
Kalbitz was one of the spokesmen of the officially dissolved "wing" around the Thuringian AfD state and faction chairman Björn Höcke; the constitutional protection classifies the tinge as "assured right-wing extremist aspiration".
In May, the AfD-Bundesvorstand had thrown Kalbitz out of the party.
As a result, he stated that Kalbitz had not stated an earlier membership in the now forbidden far-right "Heimattreuen Deutschen Jugend" (HDJ) and among the Republicans.
Kalbitz denies membership in the HDJ.
The chairman of the Left faction in the Brandenburg state parliament, Sebastian Walter, also stressed that the decision of the Federal Arbitration Court does not change the character of the AfD: "The wolf has only eaten chalk.
The AfD remains a far-right party, whether with or without Kalbitz ".
Neither the federal party nor the right wing will be weakened with this decision.
"The maneuver of the Meuthen troop is transparent.
One wants to avoid further observation by the protection of the constitution and tries to get through under the radar ", said Walter.
"The AfD does not get rid of the ghosts it called.
An ejection does not change anything, "said Erik Stohn, SPD general secretary in Brandenburg, commenting on the decision in the Kalbitz case.
"Here the AfD-Landesverband and the faction kept to their right leader".
The legal dispute over Kalbitz's membership in the AfD will continue.
He announced on Saturday that he would now proceed with civil law against the decision of the Federal Arbitration Court.
North Sea wind farms supply a good 21 percent more electricity
In the first six months of the year, the wind turbines on the German North Sea fed 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity into the grid.
This is a good 21 percent more than in the same period of the previous year, announced the grid operator Tennet in Bayreuth.
Tennet is responsible for the transmission of the North Sea electricity to the mainland and the transmission through the German electricity grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which do not belong to the grid area of Tennet, have fed a further 2.22 terawatt-hours (TWh) of electricity.
Overall, wind power from the North Sea and the Baltic Sea thus reaches 13.73 TWh, compared to a good 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The wind harvest at sea thus accounts for almost 19 percent of the total wind power in Germany, which is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms ensure higher generation capacities
In addition to the wind conditions, the increased contribution of offshore wind energy results from higher generation capacities, because new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the last twelve months.
If the 1270 wind power plants in the North Sea all run at full power at the same time, they could generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient; according to Tennet, it is 7.1 gigawatts.
By 2030, it is expected to rise to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we are investing 20 billion euros in the expansion of offshore grid connections," said TENT Managing Director Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, even at sea, wind farms cannot exploit their capacity, but reach about 40 percent.
The record day so far this year is 2 January, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce about 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, which corresponds to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply almost seven million households with electricity.
Art "Skirmish" - an exhibition of the Leipzig artist Christian Bold in the gallery of the Gmünder Kunstverein.
This was almost a small anniversary celebration for the 130.
Birthday of the Gmünder Kunstverein: The exhibition opening "Skirmish" with works by the Leipzig artist Christian Bold blew up the usual frame after the Corona break.
