Freital: Windbergfest cancelled because of Corona
The Windbergfest does not take place this year.
The city of Freital cancelled the three-day festival planned in September.
In other years, more than 30,000 people had attended this city festival.
"We really didn't make this decision easy and - aware of how difficult it is for the parties involved - hoped to reach the last minute," said Lord Mayor Uwe Rumberg (non-partisan).
"But ultimately, we are responsible for the health of many thousands of people here as organisers."
Because if tens of thousands had flowed into the grounds and into the marquee, minimum distances, hygiene regulations and contact tracking according to the current Corona protection regulation could not have been complied with.
Or the restrictions would have been so strong that there was not much left of a folk festival.
Moreover, the organisation and monitoring effort would increase disproportionately.
Rumberg rested for next year.
Then the city of Freital celebrates its 100th anniversary with the Winterberg Festival from 7 to 9 May 2021 and the Day of Saxony from 10 to 12 September 2021.
Dressage Olympic Champion Werth in Achleiten not to beat
Achleiten - Six times Olympic champion Isabell Werth was the outstanding rider at the dressage tournament in Achleiten, Austria.
The 51-year-old from Rheinberg came on the weekend with four starts to four victories.
After winning a Grand Prix with Weihegold and Quantaz, she was also unable to beat on Sunday in the Grand Prix Special and in the freestyle.
On the 15-year-old mare Weihegold, Werth won the Special on Sunday against the Austrian Victoria Max-Theurer on Abegglen.
Even in the freestyle, the Germans were clearly ahead of their 34 year old student Victoria Max-Theurer on Quantaz on Saturday.
Werth's winning horse Quantaz belongs to Max-Theurer.
The most successful dressage rider in the world should establish the ten-year-old stallion in the Grand Prix.
For Quantaz it was the first freestyle ever.
At the first tournament in Achleiten three weeks ago, Werth had already won all the important four tests.
The last of the three international tournaments is scheduled for 14 to 16 August.
More air traffic controllers in Worms in the future
The University of Worms continues to go into the air: "DFS Deutsche Flugsicherung" donates a professorship for "Air Traffic Management".
A corresponding contract between the university and DFS has now been signed in Worms.
The contract was initially concluded for three years and will start in 2021.
With the professorship, it is possible to start studying not only in the summer semester, but also in the winter semester.
This means that twice as many students can be trained as before.
At the same time, the capacities of both the university and the DFS Air Traffic Control Academy are equally utilized.
DFS will advise the university in setting up and filling the professorship.
Since 2019 represented at the university
Since the summer semester 2019, the first students in the course of their training as air traffic controllers at the University of Applied Sciences Worms are in the study program Air Traffic Management.
This year, nine students have already started.
So far, the experiences of DFS have been very positive, the students' achievements are excellent.
The combination of studies and pilot training contributes significantly to further increasing the attractiveness of the pilot's profession.
"In these times, promotion is not easy for us economically.
However, we expect air traffic to recover and grow again in the long term.
In order to continue to fulfil our legal mandate in the future, we need highly qualified personnel, "says Professor Klaus-Dieter Scheurle, Chairman of DFS when signing the contract.
"For DFS, the endowed professorship is a future-proof investment that will provide air traffic controllers with a broad, interdisciplinary knowledge base in the long term.
We therefore continue the good cooperation with the university and at the same time underpin our attractiveness as an employer ".
This is underlined by Professor Dr. Jens Hermsdorf, President of the University of Applied Sciences Worms: "The endowed professorship forms an important bridge between science and business.
With it, we would like to build on the existing cooperation with DFS Deutsche Flugsicherung as a practical partner for the dual bachelor's program Air Traffic Management. "
The trust of the German Air Traffic Control Agency is both a motivation and an obligation for the University of Applied Sciences Worms to further expand its teaching and research expertise in the fields of future aviation.
With the first endowed professorship for a dual degree program, the university can set very special highlights and innovative priorities for its students in its commitment to tomorrow's air traffic controllers.
Dr. Denis Alt, State Secretary at the Ministry of Science, Continuing Education and Culture, emphasizes: "Worms University of Applied Sciences has a unique selling point in the field of air transport in Rhineland-Palatinate.
Today's signing of the cooperation agreement strengthens the profile of the university ".
Rescue helicopter lands on the A 45
Around 30 minutes the A 45 motorway was fully closed on Saturday afternoon towards Aschaffenburg, because after a traffic accident the rescue helicopter was in use.
A 76-year-old drove with a Ford at 12.40 in the exit Alzenau-Mitte in the curve straight ahead and landed at the guardrail.
Due to the impact, the front airbags triggered, the driver suffered minor injuries on the face and had to be taken to a hospital for treatment.
The wounds of the 72-year-old passenger were treated by the emergency doctor and the patient was subsequently flown to a hospital by the rescue helicopter.
At present, however, the police assume that there is no danger of life.
The damaged vehicle, which caused damage of about 2000 euros, had to be towed.
Heil wants to test other industries after meat industry
The Corona crisis brought the conditions in parts of the meat industry to light again.
Legislative tightenings are imminent.
But are they right - and will it continue?
Federal Minister of Labour Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to check other sectors in accordance with the now planned strict regulations against maladministration in the meat industry.
"We will look at industry for industry and then take appropriate measures for the respective industry if it is necessary," Heil told the German Press Agency in Berlin.
Germany ’ s employers are already warning against restricting work contracts in general.
After the mass corona outbreak at the meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the federal cabinet wants to pass a law of salvation this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to use foreign personnel in slaughter, dismantling and meat processing.
For this purpose, the use of contract workers and temporary workers is to be prohibited there.
Employer President Ingo Kramer said the dpa: "Finger away from a general restriction of work contracts and workers' surrender if one does not want to completely strangle the economy".
Work contracts are, for example, the basis for their value-added at the customer for a wide range of craft, the construction industry and plant construction.
"The misdemeanours of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument".
Heil assured: "My goal is not to ban work contracts everywhere in the German economy."
Work contracts are useful.
"When an industrial operator orders a craftsman to install a safety system, it is a normal contract of work".
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary agency work to be unconstitutional in its sector alone.
It is unexplainable why in the future, when portioning and packaging cheese, different labour law should apply to sausage, according to a statement on the bill, as the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" (Saturday) reports.
Under a ban, the consumer price would therefore increase by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
Many Eastern European employees from contracting companies worked in the sector for 16 hours a day after the results of an audit of the NRW Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
They often had no break.
Wages were retained for protective equipment or rent.
It was also noted that the situation in the accommodation of workers was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively sharp law had already come into force for the meat industry in 2017.
However, these were circumvented by "tricky constructions".
"Now we have to clean up fundamentally".
The politician announced: "In the occupational health and safety law, which we want to pass in the cabinet at the end of July, measures are also measures that not only affect the meat industry - for example, higher occupational health and safety test rates or clear criteria for community accommodation."
The draft presented to dpa includes amendments to the Act on the Protection of Workers' Rights in the Meat Industry and to the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Brandenburg's Minister of Consumer Protection Ursula Nonnemacher (Green Party) considers more intensive controls necessary.
"I would like us to be able to make even more controls in many supervisory areas: food control, animal welfare, everything possible, including animal transport," said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB broadcast "Brandenburg aktuell".
But more personnel positions are also needed for more controls.
Three dead in the crash of ultralight aircraft in Germany
According to the police, three people died in the crash of an ultralight aircraft on an apartment building in Wesel in the German state of North Rhine-Westphalia.
One child was slightly injured.
A spokesman for the Wesel district administration said that two other people had been saved in the accident.
A parachute was found at the accident site, according to the police.
The "Rheinische Post" reported, citing eyewitnesses, that the plane had collided with a hot air balloon before the crash.
The house is a single-family or two-family house.
Further details were not initially known.
The eviction of Frankfurt Opera Square is peaceful
One week after the riots in Frankfurt, the evacuation of the Opera Square on Sunday was peaceful.
Finally, a few dozen people stayed in the square, but left him before the start of the curfew at 1 o'clock.
The police had been in action with numerous officials since the early evening, and a larger police force was to be seen throughout the city.
For the first time this weekend from midnight onwards, an entry ban was applied for the Opera Square, where riots had occurred a week ago.
Police officers were attacked with bottles out of the crowd.
At least five officers were injured after police submissions, and several police vehicles were damaged.
The night to Saturday was also quiet.
Car overturns: Young woman seriously injured in an accident on Bundesstraße 83 at Hofgeismar
In an accident between Schöneberg and Hümme, a 21-year-old suffered serious injuries at around 1.25 p.m. on Sunday.
She was taken to the Kassel Clinic.
The fire brigade used thermal cameras to search for potential passengers.
According to the police, the woman was on the road 83 towards her place of residence Hümme on the way, when her car came off the road for reasons that had not yet been clarified and overturned several times.
In order to save the victims, the fire brigade had to cut the roof of the car.
Since it was unclear whether someone was still in the vehicle, the adjacent maize field was searched from the rotary ladder with a thermal imager.
The Drohnenstaffel from Warburg, which also works with thermal imaging cameras, had also been ordered for the search for people.
However, the volunteers did not find anyone between the high corn plants.
The severely injured was taken to the hospital in Kassel with the ambulance for further care.
Almost 50 volunteers from the Hofgeismar, Hümme and Schöneberg fire brigades were present.
The highway was closed for two hours due to the accident.
Juventus Turin Champion in Italy
Turin - After a redeeming goal by Cristiano Ronaldo, record champion Juventus Turin has secured the Italian championship for the ninth time in series.
The team around the five-time world footballer made the 36th Scudetto in club history perfect with a 2: 0 (1: 0) on Sunday night in the home match against Sampdoria Genoa.
Ronaldo scored 1 – 0 in the first half.
With 83 points, Turin, who competed without the last long-injured former international Sami Khedira, is no longer out of place one two matchdays before the end of the season of Serie A.
Inter Milan is seven points behind.
Juventus was harmless in the first half despite optical superiority, then Ronaldo hit after a free kick variant with the last action.
A match by Miralem Pjanic directly exploited the 35-year-old from the penalty space limit with a flat shot (45. + 7).
Ronaldo also took part in the 2: 0 against the now more offensive guests, after his shot Federico Bernardeschi dusted off (67.).
This was the perfect but decisive success.
The foul elfmeter shot to the bar in the 89th minute is probably only Ronaldo himself with regard to the goal hunter-scoring.
"It's complicated to stay at ball height mentally and physically for 90 minutes.
The games are weird, and momentum is changing very slightly, "said coach Maurizio Sarri after a 1 – 2 win at Udinese Calcio on Thursday.
Especially the mental exhaustion of his players is great, said the Juve-Coach.
Because of the defeat, the Turiners had not yet been able to make the championship perfect.
In the end, Juve had to owe the reassuring advantage at the top of the table to the weakness of the competitors.
Because in the eleven games before the game on Sunday, the Sarri-team only managed five victories.
Whether Ronaldo also becomes the goalscorer king is questionable.
While the Portuguese superstar has scored 31 goals so far, the former Ciro Immobile from Dortmund has already scored 34 goals in his account at Hellas Verona in the 5: 1 (1: 1) of Lazio Rome - as many as Robert Lewandowski contributed to the title win of FC Bayern.
The current Juve professional Gonzalo Higuaín holds the record in Italy.
In the 2015 / 2016 season the Argentine scored 36 goals for the SSC Naples.
The next title chance awaits the "old lady" of Italian football in August.
Juventus is in the eighth final of the Champions League, but on 7 August they have to make up for a 0: 1 first leg defeat to Olympique Lyon in order to reach the final tournament in Lisbon.
In the next knockout round, Real Madrid or Manchester City would wait as opponents.
Baden-Württemberg: Over 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all the punishments and court judgments threatened, motorists continue to gas in countless illegal races on Baden-Württemberg's roads: last year and the first four months of this year, police in the southwest have already registered more than 250 illegal car races.
Comparative figures for the years before do not exist, but the racers are increasingly doing work for the judicial authorities: In 2018, a total of 155 investigations were conducted with the prosecutors between Konstanz and Mannheim for illegal races, one year later there were already 252 and in the current year to the beginning of June 151.
The races were less about organized events, as can be seen from the response of the Ministry of the Interior to a request from the Landtag SPD.
In most cases, the drivers are spontaneously competing against each other or they have taken flight from the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
German men aged between 18 and 60 were mainly at the wheel.
113 fines - 15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the racers caught and also asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, since 2018 a total of 113 fines have been imposed and 15 prison sentences pronounced.
However, there is no evidence that the number of illegal car races actually increases.
Rather, other drivers reacted more sensitively than they did in the past due to the many tragic accidents and processes, and reported more frequently, said a minister spokesman.
The freeway 8 is particularly popular with racers. Time and again, motorists stop traffic there in order to make room for themselves and use the free track for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 riders on the A8 at Merklingen.
A81 is the most popular "race track"
On the A81, the police register even more races than on any other federal highway.
A speed limit is used to try to slow down the speeders on the particularly affected section between narrowness and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and mutilated sports and luxury bodies often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers dodge to Germany because of the high penalties for too fast driving and car racing in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few routes: "With a general speed limit of 130 km / h, we would be able to deal with this problem on motorways," says Martin Rivoir, the transport expert of the SPD parliamentary group in the state parliament.
"The obstacle threshold for racers would be significantly higher if you are not allowed to travel here and there legally with 200 km / h and more".
Rivoir thinks less of enlightenment or image campaigns: "Anyone who in such a way overrides all rules and puts not only his own life, but also the life of other road users at risk, is hardly reachable with reason".
ADAC calls for stronger police intervention
On the other hand, this is not enough for the ADAC: "We assume that Raser will not be deterred by the speed limits," says Holger Bach, Head of Transport and Environment at ADAC Württemberg.
It calls for additional and tougher controls on the affected routes.
It is not uncommon for the high-touring power test to be painful and severe: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people have died in the races nationwide, two of them uninvolved in a nightly crash in Stuttgart's city centre and one in Gerlingen.
There, two young men are said to have completed a car race in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, bounced against a garden wall and remained on the side, the 18-year-old passenger died.
21 more people were injured in the races of the past two years.
However, in the opinion of Interior Minister Thomas Strobl, stricter penalties are not necessary: "Legislative action is not required to sanction illegal motor vehicle races harder," says the paper of the Ministry of the Interior.
Blue light from July 23: Thirsty burglar steals drinks from snacks
Rohrdorf: A man broke into a snack on Thursday in Rohrdorf (Calw district) and stole drinks and cash.
A witness heard noise in the valley road around 3.40 a.m. and ran towards the snack bar.
There he noticed a man who used to drink at the fridge and then left the snack through a previously opened entrance door.
The perpetrator fled towards the meadows behind the snack.
According to the police, the burglar also used a cash register and stole cash in the low three-digit range.
The suspect is described as follows: He is about 1.75 to 1.80 meters tall and of strong stature.
In fact, he wore a black hoodie, black pants and bright shoes.
The police accept further testimony.
Ackermann sprints to victory on final stage at Sibiu Tour
Radprofi Pascal Ackermann won his second day victory on the final stage of the 10th Sibiu Tour.
The 26-year-old Pfälzer from Team Bora-hansgrohe won the mass sprint on the 109 km long section with start and finish in Sibiu, after he had already won a stage on Saturday.
It was the season's three and four victories for Ackermann.
In the overall standings, his Austrian teammate Gregor Mühlberger prevailed.
The 26-year-old had masterfully won the mountain time trial in the morning and thus took over the top of the class.
Only 104 drivers were left in the evening for the final stage.
No less than 18 starters had fallen victim to the time limit in the mountain time trial.
"I'm really happy to start the new season with a win," Ackermann explained after his success on Saturday.
"The sprint was really hectic," said the 26-year-old.
300 meters before the finish, he simply put on his sprint, "and it worked perfectly".
According to the rules of the World Federation UCI, a Corona test was carried out six days before the start of the race.
During the entire tour, drivers and supervisors were separated in insulated hygiene bubbles from the organizing team and the media.
Spectators at the start and finish were not allowed.
Control center gave instruction to lay reanimation
Düsseldorf - Tragic accident on Sunday afternoon in Düsseldorf-Garath.
In an apartment house, a child (4) suddenly lay lifeless in the water while bathing.
According to the fire department, the emergency call was received at just before 13: 00.
"A control center dispatcher immediately gave instructions for layman reanimation," a fire service spokesman said to BILD.
The rescuers arrived a little later and took the resuscitation measures.
The child in danger of life was transported to the university hospital under reanimation.
