Nuremberg: Unapproved tuning meeting - police intervenes, 700 vehicles and around 1100 people
Hundreds of cars and temporarily over 1000 people took part in a "tuning meeting" on Saturday night in the parking lot of a furniture store.
The police implemented their announcement to intensify the control of such events.
A big tuning meeting took place on Saturday evening (July 25, 2020) in Nuremberg's Südstadt.
Several hundred vehicles were involved.
According to the police in central Franconia, an increased volume of vehicles in the area of a large parking lot in Ingolstädter Straße had been determined by the Nuremberg traffic police at around 10.30 p.m..
The police then carried out a large number of vehicle inspections there.
Only recently, the police had announced that they would step up the fight against so-called Autoposers.
Illegal tuning meeting in Nuremberg: Only a small part of the "scene"
The officers counted to the top about 700 vehicles and about 1100 people, the police accounted for.
Of this, however, only a small part of those present are to be attributed to the "Autoposer" and tuning scene.
Apparently, most of the relevant scene followed the appeal of the police.
On the basis of the vehicles and people on site, it can be assumed that these were predominantly spectators.
In addition, the overwhelming proportion of those present adhered to the prevailing infection protection provisions, in particular compliance with the minimum distance and wearing a word-of-mouth protection.
The control measures carried out on the ground were completed at 1: 00 a.m.
All in all, the officials found such structural changes in 10 vehicles that the operating permit had expired.
Four of these vehicles had to be secured.
No car races
There were no illegal car races.
"The police headquarters of Central Franconia will continue to keep an eye on what is happening and will continue to carry out enhanced control measures, also in connection with the advent of spectators," it said.
The agency News5 spoke to Jürgen Schrödinger of the towing company involved: "They all have beautiful rims, we must not scratch them," says Schrödinger.
For this, special tapes would be used.
Also because the cars are wider, the company must be careful not to make any damage.
"After all, the young people are supposed to get their cars back without prejudice."
Employment Agency figures: 900 suspected cases of abuse of short-time work
Berlin - The Federal Employment Agency (BA), according to its own statement, investigates about 900 suspected cases of abuse of the short-time work allowance.
"This is extremely little for more than 880,000 companies that have reported short-time work," said Daniel Terzenbach, Executive Board member responsible for operational business, of the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung".
When, at the beginning of the Corona crisis, many companies suddenly applied for short-time work, the BA had to react quickly.
Usually the test takes up to three weeks.
"So much time was not available to us in this hot phase.
We will therefore take a closer look at the final accounts.
Certainly there will be a lot to follow.
We are not naive and have a long breath. "
Evidence of abuse often comes from the affected employees or trade unions.
In addition, use the BA analysis software to detect abuse patterns.
According to Terzenbach, the BA is preparing for a possible wave of insolvency in autumn.
"Will there be significantly more insolvencies than in the previous year?
The assessments differ, but we prepare ourselves for the case and already now train our employees in the employment agencies for the processing of applications for insolvency money ".
The figures are still inconspicuous, said Terzenbach.
World Heritage in Potsdam: Party in the New Garden dissolved
Potsdam - On Friday evening about 40 young people celebrated a party in the New Garden.
The collection was dissolved at 8.48 p.m. by the district drivers of the Stiftung Preußische Schlösser und Gärten (SPSG), the foundation announced on PNN request.
The teenagers then left the park.
On Saturday evening, some young people would have played rugby in the New Garden.
SPSG spokesman Frank Kallensee said on Sunday that the meadow had been cleared by district drivers.
Time and again there are illegal celebrations in the parks
In the Foundation's parks, accumulations occur time and again, in which the distance and hygiene rules COVID-19 Ordinance are not complied with.
At the end of June there was a celebration with about 300 people in the park Babelsberg, a week later about 150 people celebrated in the New Garden.
Even without a coronary order, the parks are closed at nightfall.
The storage on the meadows is prohibited according to park regulations, there are only a few exceptions.
The Foundation has been complaining for a long time that visitors are leaving more and more waste and destroying protected biotopes.
In Berlin, illegal park parties have meanwhile reached a different dimension.
In the Hasenheide in the district of Neukölln, 5000 people celebrated an illegal techno party on Sunday night.
The event was dissolved by the police.
Austria: Mass tests after Corona eruption in tourist resort
With hundreds of tests, authorities have responded to a Corona outbreak in the popular Upper Austrian tourist resort of St. Wolfgang.
The number of confirmed cases rose to 48, as reported by the state authorities in Linz.
More than 100 results were still pending in the evening.
According to this, many of the infected are young interns in tourism companies, but at least one holiday guest has also been tested positive.
Residents, guests and tourism staff were asked to stay in their accommodation on Saturday night.
The closing hour was set at 23: 00.
"There are cancellations and cancellations there and there" of bookings, said the head of the tourism association Wolfgangsee, Hans Wieser, the dpa.
Some of the guests also left early.
St. Wolfgang is the most important tourist resort in Upper Austria, with more than 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season, about a third of the guests are Germans.
On Friday, the first infections had become publicly known.
The head of the district authority, Alois Lanz, defended on Saturday the behavior of the interns, who had celebrated in several restaurants and could have been infected there.
"We all liked to do this in our youth," he said to the radio station Ö1.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The tourism association launched an information campaign to raise awareness among young employees about the dangers of COVID-19.
From Saturday, hundreds of employees, holidaymakers and locals were tested.
In addition, all guests who were in St. Wolfgang from 15 July were contacted.
The eruption evokes memories of the Austrian ski and party resort of Ischgl in Tyrol, which in the early phase of the pandemic was a center of the Corona spread throughout Europe.
In total, more than 1500 people in Austria are currently infected with the virus.
The focus of new infections is on Vienna and Upper Austria.
