North Korea closes border city after Corona suspected case
North Korea has so far seen a "brilliant success" in its own measures to defend the coronavirus.
Now the country is reporting on a suspected case for the first time.
Because of a first official corona suspicion in the country, North Korea has completely closed off a big city for fear of a catastrophe.
Despite the strictest epidemiological defenses in the past six months, "the malignant virus may have been introduced into the country," the state media reported.
For the region around the border town Kaesong the state of emergency had been imposed.
The Communist leadership declared the highest level of alarm.
If the suspected case is confirmed, it would be the first official infection case with Sars-CoV-2 in the isolated country.
North Korea had so far not registered a single infection and described its defenses as "brilliant success".
The information was disputed abroad.
The disease symptoms were reportedly found in a "outlier" who illegally crossed the military demarcation line between South and North Korea on 19 July.
The person had settled down three years ago in South Korea and had now returned across the border.
For the crossing of the border within the four kilometres wide and largely still mined military buffer zone, there was initially no confirmation from South Korea.
According to reports from the national news agency Yonhap, South Korea's military acknowledged the possibility of an illegal border crossing to North Korea as high.
There have been investigations into some people.
North Korea called an emergency meeting of the Workers' Party's Politburo, chaired by Kim Jong Un, on Saturday because of the suspicion.
The "dangerous situation in Kaesong could trigger a deadly and destructive catastrophe".
Kim had already ordered on Friday as a preventive measure to "completely block Kaesong and isolate each district and the region from others," it continued.
The affected person and all the people in Kaesong who had been in contact with her were quarantined.
The central military commission of the party should therefore investigate the "outbreak" and the behavior of the responsible military unit and, if necessary, impose a hard punishment.
It is estimated that about 300,000 people live in Kaesong.
