Hurricane "Hanna" reaches Texas: Help made difficult because of Corona
Washington - The first hurricane of this year's season across the Atlantic has landed in Texas.
Life-threatening floods, strong winds and heavy rainfall now threaten parts of the US state, the National Hurricane Center of the US Climate Agency (NOAA) reported on Sunday (local time) at night.
Governor Greg Abbott declared a state of emergency for many districts.
The Texas Corona pandemic made the work of the helpers harder, Abbott continued, according to the US media.
Evacuated people called to caution
"Every hurricane is a huge challenge," Abbott said, according to the Houston Chronicle.
In view of the hurricane in Texas, he added, "This challenge is complicated and aggravated, considering that it sweeps through an area that is the state's most affected area by Covid-19."
According to the Johns Hopkins University, the corona pandemic has killed around 5,000 people in Texas alone.
Abbott called people who had to leave their homes to be careful.
They should not disregard practices "we have become accustomed to", such as wearing masks, said the governor according to CBS.
It was important that everyone kept a distance.
For this reason, hotel rooms were also provided in some places.
In addition, it should be tested in emergency shelters on Corona.
Damage was initially reported only from the coastal town of Port Mansfield.
Storm warning withdrawn again
With wind speeds of up to 150 kilometres per hour, "Hanna", according to authorities, was hit on land on the island of Padre Island just off the Texas coast.
The tropical storm had previously been upgraded to the lowest level hurricane.
For the coastal section from Port Mansfield to Sargent, a storm surge warning was issued and later withdrawn.
Authorities expected a weakening, while "Hanna" moved inland and headed for northeastern Mexico.
"Douglas" moves to Hawaii
In the Pacific, Hurricane "Douglas" travelled to Hawaii overnight on Sunday with wind speeds of around 150 kilometres per hour.
The hurricane center, however, expected to weaken further.
According to the forecast, it should be near the largest islands of Hawaii on Sunday (local time) - then as a storm just below the hurricane threshold.
Over the Atlantic, NOAA anticipated an above-average hurricane season this year after a May forecast.
From June to the end of November, up to ten hurricanes could be expected, of which up to six could be very strong cyclones, the authority said.
On average, there are six hurricanes per year across the Atlantic, three of which develop into storms of great strength.
In view of the available climate data and the higher water temperature in the Atlantic and the Caribbean, the probability of a normal season is only 30 percent, the one below average even only 10 percent, it was said back then.
US President Donald Trump wrote on Twitter that his government closely monitors the storms and is in contact with the affected states.
