Formula 1 needs a special rule to select its world champion
Since it is not possible to drive on the required number of continents, the FIA must improvise to award the World Cup titles.
All races were cancelled.
Racing calendar is becoming more and more concrete
The racing calendar of the current Formula 1 season continues to take shape.
In addition to the ten confirmed Grand Prix, three other race tracks were added during the week.
In October, the Nürburgring will be held in Germany and in Portimão, Portugal.
On the first of November, Lewis Hamilton and Co. compete for World Championship points at the traditional Italian race track in Imola.
This means that the 2020 racing calendar currently comprises 13 races.
"We are pleased to continue to make great progress in completing our plans for the 2020 season," said Formula 1 boss Chase Carey.
A total of 15 to 18 races in the premier class of motorsport are scheduled for this extraordinary season.
The Formula 1 will conclude its season in Asia.
The final race calendar is to be fixed and published in the coming weeks.
Prior to the already officially scheduled races in Bahrain and Abu Dhabi in December, according to media reports, appearances could still take place in Vietnam and Malaysia at the end of November.
Regulations require races on three continents
The regulations of Formula 1 require at least races on three continents for the award of the World Cup.
Even if, as currently planned, only two continents will be driven, there will be a world champion.
With the help of a special rule, the FIA wants to award the titles based on "extraordinary circumstances" due to the coronavirus pandemic.
The traditional start of the season in Australia in March had to be cancelled at short notice due to the onset of the Corona crisis.
A return to the continent this year is not an issue.
In addition, Formula 1 will not be a guest in America this year.
Cancellation meets with criticism in Brazil
Due to the tense corona situation, the races will not take place in Canada, the USA, Mexico and Brazil.
"We look forward to being back next season," Carey said.
The refusal of the American races met with criticism, especially in Brazil: "The refusal did not come as a surprise for us, but we cannot accept the reasons for it," said Tamas Rohonyi, promoter of the Grand Prix in São Paulo.
Infection rates in the São Paulo area are significantly lower than in other regions of Brazil.
The concerns of some teams not wanting to drive in Brazil would also not justify a refusal.
We are prepared for the required safety measures.
